Run trajectory analysis with Lagranto¶

Lagrangian analysis tool Lagranto provides provide functionalities to calcualte Lagrangian trajectories from reanalysis data. Lagranto is origionally written in FORTRAN and excuted in bash script. A python wrapper of Lagranto is created to run Lagranto in Jupyter notebook.

In this notebook, we will go through steps of calculating trajectories.

In [6]:
statdir = f"{work_dir}/startf/startf.fortranonlyT"

P files should be ready before running Lagranto in this notebook.

At an instanously time, a P file contains:

  • U (three-dimensional zonal wind)
  • V (three-dimensional meridional wind)
  • OMEGA (three-dimensional vertical velocity in Pa/s)
  • PS (two-dimensional surface pressure)

⚠️ Note: These four variables are compulsory for running trajectories!

A P file is netcdf file, named as PYYYYMMdd_HH, in which YYYY represents year, MM represent month, dd represent day, and HH represents hour, e.g., P20241202_12

An exmaple P file (P20241202_12) is shown below:

To run trajectory, multiple P files are needed, e.g.,
P20241201_00, P20241201_06, P20241201_18, P20241202_00, ...

P files are generated using the Python script get_Pfile.py under work_dir. For submitting PBS job, user can use get_Pfile.sh

Step 2 - We now generate some starting positions

For starting positions in a box, using create_starf_box

Parameters:

  • statdir - directory of starting positions as set before
  • lon_min - lower bound of longitude
  • lon_max - upper bound of longitude
  • lat_min - lower bound of latitude
  • lat_max - upper bound of latitude
  • interval - grid spacing in degree
  • lev_range - list of pressure levels
In [8]:
create_starf_box(statdir, 140 ,150, 30, 40, 1, [925, 800, 700, 600, 500])

Step 3 - Calculate trajectory with Lagranto python wrapper

For starting positions in a box, using run_Lagranto

Parameters:

  • statdir - directory of starting positions as set before
  • period - length of period (in hours). Minus sigh indicates backward trajectory, e.g., -120 means 120 hours backward
  • outputdir - directory where output data (trajectory) is located
  • input_interval - time interval for input P files (in minitues, e.g., 360 minitues = 6 hours)
  • output_interval - time interval for output trajectory files (in minitues, e.g., 360 minitues = 6 hours)
  • reference_date - the start date when trajectories are calcualted
  • era5dir - directory where P files are located
  • quiet - False or True

For the example, we would like to calcualte 120-hour bacjkward trajectories (period=-120), starting at UTC 12 on 2nd December 2024 (reference_date="20241202_12")

In [9]:
reference_date = "20241202_12"
period = -120 

run_Lagranto(statdir, period, outpdir, 360, 360, reference_date, era5dir,
             quiet=True)

The output trajectories are read into pandas dataframe using modify_lagranto_output.
